data_tsibble <- data %>%

# Split the data into training and testing sets

test_data <- data_tsibble[(train_size + 1):nrow(data_tsibble), ]

# Fit an ARIMA model on the training data

1b.

We selected monthly time series of Brent crude oil prices from FRED and was first transformed into a tsibble format suitable for time series forecasting. The dataset was then divided into training and testing sets, with 70% allocated for training to ensure robust model training while retaining 30% for testing to validate model predictions. We build ARIMA model,did residual diagnostics to ensure that the residuals resembled white noise, indicating a good fit.

The ARIMA model’s performance was assessed using the RMSE. The RMSE obtained was 20.87786 Subsequently, an ETS model was also fitted and compared to the ARIMA model. Despite the slight difference in RMSE,we selected the ARIMA model for future forecasting due to its marginally lower RMSE, indicating slightly better performance. Ultimately, a one-year-ahead forecast was generated using the chosen ARIMA model, visualized alongside confidence intervals to provide a prospective view of expected price movements and associated uncertainty, aiding in future planning and decision-making processes.

# 2a. Get Quandl's CPI information and  S&P 500 Price Index.

cpi_monthly <- Quandl("FRED/CPIAUCNS", collapse = "monthly")
sp500_monthly <- Quandl("MULTPL/SP500_REAL_PRICE_MONTH", collapse = "monthly")

# Integrate data from the S&P 500 and the CPI.
combined_data <- inner_join(cpi_monthly, sp500_monthly, by = "Date")


# Find the S&P 500 Price Index's actual value.
combined_data <- combined_data %>%
  mutate(real_sp500 = Value.y * (Value.x[1] / Value.x))


# Plot the S&P 500 Price Index's real and nominal values.
ggplot(combined_data, aes(x = Date)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = Value.y, color = "Nominal")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = real_sp500, color = "Real")) +
  labs(title = "Distinguishing between the Nominal and Real S&P 500 Price Index",
       y = "Price Index") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Nominal" = "red", "Real" = "black")) +
  theme_minimal()

# Predict the actual value of the S&P 500 Price Index over the following six months.
sp500_model <- auto.arima(combined_data$real_sp500)
sp500_forecast <- forecast(sp500_model, h = 6)

# Plot forecasted values
autoplot(sp500_forecast) +
  labs(title = "Predicted future value of the S&P 500 Price Index for the next six months.")

# Determine the rate of return for the S&P 500 Price Index based on its nominal value.
combined_data <- combined_data %>%
  mutate(return = (Value.y - lag(Value.y)) / lag(Value.y))

# Returns Plot
ggplot(combined_data, aes(x = Date, y = return)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "S&P 500 Price Index returns",
       y = "Returns") +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Removed 1 row containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_line()`).

# Projected returns for the upcoming six months
arima_model <- auto.arima(combined_data$return)
arima_forecast <- forecast(arima_model, h = 6)

# Plot forecasted returns
autoplot(arima_forecast) +
  labs(title = "Forecasted returns of the nominal S&P 500 price index for the next 6 months")

# 3a.
combined_tsibble <- combined_data %>%
  mutate(Date = as.Date(Date)) %>%
  as_tsibble(index = Date) %>%
  mutate(Month = month(Date, label = TRUE))

#Average index value by month
average_index <- combined_tsibble %>%
  group_by(Month) %>%
  summarise(Avg_Index = mean(Value.y, na.rm = TRUE))

# Plotting the average index value per month
ggplot(average_index, aes(x = Month, y = Avg_Index)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "blue") +
  labs(title = "Monthly Average S&P 500 Price Index", x = "Month", y = "Average Index Value") +
  theme_minimal()

# Regression model to consider seasonality
regression_model <- lm(Value.y ~ Month, data = combined_tsibble)

# Summary of the regression model
summary_regression <- summary(regression_model)
print(summary_regression)

3b.

This question involved using the monthly S&P 500 Price Index data to analyze seasonal effects. A tsibble dataset was created for time series analysis. Initial plots of average index values by month showed that December did not consistently show the highest index values.

A regression model incorporating month as a predictor identified which month historically had the greatest impact on the index. The results indicated that no single month significantly outperformed others at a 5% significance level, suggesting that month alone might not be a reliable predictor of S&P 500 performance.

The analysis was deepened by considering whether the overall model was statistically significant and exploring investment implications based on predictive power.
